reviews.text: Very small museum, cool knowledgeable guides that seem to master a lot of the countrie's historic, traditional and mythological stories. In an hour you can see most part of it. There is a little shop outside of the museum where you can buy some artifacts that are also available elsewhere at lesser price.
I like this place but I would love it if it had enough traditional and local object. I think it doesn't represent enough the national heritage

I loved visiting this museum. I wish I could've taken pictures. Nevertheless, our tour guide, William Dayo, was very well versed in each of the exhibits. It was really nice to have someone with us who gave us in depth information on what we were viewing. It gave us a deeper understanding and appreciation for each of the artifacts.
It was nice. The museum has a lot to offer in cultural history and I was happy to see them opened on a Sunday.

This museum continues the tradition of equating Western African culture and history mainly with masks (sarcasm). It could almost be interchangeable with the museum's in Dakar and Bamako except they both have a second floor dedicated to textiles. 

Granted, the masks are interesting and high quality, but they are completely decontextualized with cryptic captions an little explanation tying anything together.

There is one table showing the evolution of money that was nice. 

It's one of the few times I wished there was a museum gift shop with some books. 

Weirdly they don't allow photography either, as if history should be hidden. 

Avoid the restaurant out back it is way overpriced and there are better maquis around.

Best place to visit . It is found inside Addis Ababa university , College of natural and computational science compound .
Several wild animals are found reserved ( killed and dried ) 
It has entrance fee 
For regular students (AAU students ) and children - 5 birr
For adult Ethiopians - 15 birr
For foreigners - 100 birr 
If you want to record and take a picture you have to pay another fee .
But all the payments are totally worth it .
I RECOMMEND YOU TO VISIT THIS PLACE .
Museum was closed despite that it's supposed to be opened.  No explanations.  Don't bother going.
It is consist of historical and inspire objects.
Easy to miss. Still worth a walk through for the insect and mammal collections, modest though they are. Gives a sense of the biological  diversity of the country.

You'd be surprised to think it's the end of the world when shopping in this place!

The shelves literally have nothing on them, when they do you might want to grab it then and there as you may never see it again with the stock changing almost every day, some of the things you want you will never find, the prices are crazy for just the basics (Like £7 for a box of cereal!!) and it's literally a ghost town almost every day when you walk in it as parts of the shop look abandoned or just plain empty.

I would recommend the local shop just south from this one on the marina, has more in it and the prices are much more reasonable. 

This one is just way too overpriced for what its meant to be. Do not recommend!
